    <h1>Hot Dried Chilli Pep&#xAD;per Chicken ($32.80)</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200830/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-30"><time>2020-08-30</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Nalati’s ren­di­tion of the clas­sic tongue-numb­ing la zi ji is sur­pris­ingly le­git for a non-Sichuan restau­rant.</p>
    <p>There is enough fire from the dried chill­ies to send streams of sweat down my brow as I tuck into the ad­dic­tive dish. But even as my mouth starts burn­ing, I can­not stop down­ing one piece af­ter an­other.</p>
    <p>The chef uses chopped chicken wing with bone in. While this means you need to avoid the bones, the chicken skin keeps the meat juicy.</p>

